<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-hvnkNar9AoySrG4rOTPvug" name="attributes,_gZG0kHRtEd2-O6kr4zpk8g" guid="-hvnkNar9AoySrG4rOTPvug" version="7.5.0">
  <sections xmi:id="_OJEwcHrIEd29Rtf8hOMN0w" name="Have all the necessary attributes been defined?" guid="_OJEwcHrIEd29Rtf8hOMN0w">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Requirements attributes that support the project need to be defined prior to recording the requirements. Every&#xD;
    project&amp;nbsp;must consider maintaining a minimal set of requirements attributes to support tracking and managing&#xD;
    requirements (see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.tech.rqmts_mgmt.base-ibm/guidances/examples/core_requirements_attributes_3FF52DA1.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_wq3oUHRsEd2-O6kr4zpk8g&quot;>Example: Core Requirements Attributes&lt;/a>). See &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../../practice.tech.rqmts_mgmt.base-ibm/guidances/examples/extended_requirements_attributes_8D77E7C1.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_2ap1oHRsEd2-O6kr4zpk8g&quot;>Example: Extended Requirements Attributes&lt;/a> for an extended list of attributers to&#xD;
    consider.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br /></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_udb9wHrKEd29Rtf8hOMN0w" name="Is it clear who is responsible for updating requirements attributes?" guid="_udb9wHrKEd29Rtf8hOMN0w">
    <sectionDescription>Without a clear understanding of the importance of the requirements attributes, project team members&amp;nbsp;can either&#xD;
neglect to update them, or update them in an incomplete way. Anyone with responsibility for managing requirements must be&#xD;
given brief background information or training to be able to set the values in a meaningful way, and must agree to ensure&#xD;
that the attributes are properly populated.</sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_PaWLEHrIEd29Rtf8hOMN0w" name="Will the attribute usually be used to research, track, or manage requirements, or to select a subset of requirements?" guid="_PaWLEHrIEd29Rtf8hOMN0w">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Avoid attributes that convey information with limited or no value to the project team. If little value can be discerned&#xD;
    in the attribute, then do not include it.&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_-9ejcHrcEd29Rtf8hOMN0w" name="Will the attribute value not be set to the default value most of the time?" guid="_-9ejcHrcEd29Rtf8hOMN0w">
    <sectionDescription>Attributes that will usually be set to the default value generally can&amp;nbsp;be avoided, because they increase requirements&#xD;
management without providing much value.</sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_NFPvYHrdEd29Rtf8hOMN0w" name="Is the attribute recorded in only one place?" guid="_NFPvYHrdEd29Rtf8hOMN0w">
    <sectionDescription>There is also the potential to duplicate tracking that occurs elsewhere. For example, keeping the planned iteration as a&#xD;
requirements attribute&amp;nbsp;might duplicate information that is kept in project plans. Remove the duplication, or leverage&#xD;
some higher-level traceability to ensure that someone will be aware that changes to the attribute need to be propagated to&#xD;
that higher-level traceability.</sectionDescription>
  </sections>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription>
